lego:evidence  a  owl:AnnotationProperty .

gomodel:SYNGO_5174  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 5: The mixed CBR agonists 2-AG and WIN,55212-2 (WIN) as well as the CB2R-specific agonist HU-308 (HU) all strongly hyperpolarized CA3 PCs in WT mice. Specificity of targeting CB2R was validated with CB2R-/- mice. Neither of the drugs led to a hyperpolarization in these animals, strongly arguing for a purely CB2R-dependent mechanism (Figures 5D-5F).\n\nFigure 6: \"As CBRs are G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs), we confirmed that the hyperpolarization is mediated by a G protein-dependent cascade by performing experiments with 0.5 mM GDPβS, a non-hydrolyzable GDP analog that blocks G protein-coupled activity. The inclusion of GDPβS into the pipette abolished the pharmacologically induced hyperpolarization within the manipulated neuron (Figures 6A and 6B), supporting the idea of a cell-intrinsic, G protein-dependent mechanism.\"\n\n\"Highlights\n- CB2Rs are expressed in hippocampal principal neurons\n- CB2Rs mediate a cell type-specific self-inhibitory plasticity in CA3/CA2 PCs\n- CB2Rs reduce the spike probability of CA3 PCs and alter gamma oscillations in vivo\n- CB2Rs act complementary to presynaptic CB1Rs\". Experimental description: Results: \"The mixed CBR agonists 2-AG and WIN,55212-2 (WIN) as well as the CB2R-specific agonist HU-308 (HU) all strongly hyperpolarized CA3 PCs in WT mice (Figures 5A-5C, 5E, and 5F).\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" ;
        dc:date           "2023-02-26" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5174" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

